<quantity box="[832,961,265,289]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2999999999999998" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="14" pageNumber="117" unit="mm" value="1.2999999999999998" valueMax="1.4" valueMin="1.2">1.2–1.4 mm</quantity>
. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[1153,1214,265,289]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="6.[189,229,1981,2003]" captionTargetBox="[195,1433,232,1956]" captionTargetId="figure-94@6.[189,1436,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1–8: Male habitusof Leptusaspp.1 – L.excisa; 2 – L.grandipennis; 3– L.auriculata; 4– L.gonggana; 5– L.emeiana; 6 – L. jizuica;" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5743066" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5743066/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
. Colouration: forebody reddish-brown to dark-brown, often with the head at least partly darker; abdomen with segments III–IV reddish-brown to blackish, V–VII blackish, and VIII–X dark-yellow to reddish; legs and antennae reddish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[831,1437,233,1441]" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[912,988,425,449]" captionStart="Figs 9–18" captionStartId="7.[151,191,1982,2004]" captionTargetBox="[153,1398,232,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9–18: Male habitus (9–11) and forebody (12–18) of Leptusa spp. 9, 15 – L. habana; 10 – L. monscangi; 11 – L. pathibarana; 12 – L. excisa; 13 – L. grandipennis; 14 – L. gonggana; 16 – L. auriculata; 17 – L. jizuica; 18 – L. desculpens. Scale bars:9–16: 1.0 mm; 17–18: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5743070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5743070/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
) transverse; punctation coarse, dense, and umbilicate; interstices narrower than diameter of punctures, with shallow microsculpture. Eyes slightly shorter than postocular region in lateral view. Antennae slender, gradually and moderately incrassate apically, preapical antennomeres approximately 1.5 times as broad as long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[831,1437,233,1441]" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[968,1043,649,673]" captionStart="Figs 9–18" captionStartId="7.[151,191,1982,2004]" captionTargetBox="[153,1398,232,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9–18: Male habitus (9–11) and forebody (12–18) of Leptusa spp. 9, 15 – L. habana; 10 – L. monscangi; 11 – L. pathibarana; 12 – L. excisa; 13 – L. grandipennis; 14 – L. gonggana; 16 – L. auriculata; 17 – L. jizuica; 18 – L. desculpens. Scale bars:9–16: 1.0 mm; 17–18: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5743070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5743070/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
) 1.3–1.4 times as broad as long and approximately 1.3 times as broad as head; maximal width slightly anterior to middle; posterior angles obtusely marked; punctation finer, shallower, and less defined than that of head; interstices with shallow microsculpture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[831,1437,233,1441]" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">
Elytra (
<figureCitation box="[916,991,841,865]" captionStart="Figs 9–18" captionStartId="7.[151,191,1982,2004]" captionTargetBox="[153,1398,232,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9–18: Male habitus (9–11) and forebody (12–18) of Leptusa spp. 9, 15 – L. habana; 10 – L. monscangi; 11 – L. pathibarana; 12 – L. excisa; 13 – L. grandipennis; 14 – L. gonggana; 16 – L. auriculata; 17 – L. jizuica; 18 – L. desculpens. Scale bars:9–16: 1.0 mm; 17–18: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5743070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5743070/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
) 0.70–0.75 times as long as pronotum; punctation dense and much coarser than that of pronotum. Hind wings completely reduced.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[831,1437,233,1441]" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">Abdomen broader than elytra; punctation distinct and rather dense; interstices with microreticulation; posterior margin of tergite VII with narrow rudiment of a palisade fringe; tergite VII without, tergite VIII with weakly pronounced sexual dimorphism.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[831,1437,233,1441]" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">
: tergite VIII (Fig. 48) with weakly concave posterior margin; sternite VII posteriorly truncate or very weakly concave, with long marginal setae; posterior margin of sternite VIII convexly produced in the middle (Fig. 56); median lobe of aedeagus nearly 
<quantity box="[1181,1263,1225,1249]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="117" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
long, shaped as in Figs 45–47; apical lobe of paramere of similar shape as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="PACE" authorityYear="1997" box="[859,980,1289,1313]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Leptusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="117" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chinensis">
<emphasis box="[859,980,1289,1313]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">L. chinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[831,1437,233,1441]" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">: tergite VIII (Fig. 49) with weakly concave or truncate posterior margin; posterior margin of sternite VIII broadly and obtusely angled in the middle (Fig. 57); spermatheca (Fig. 50) not distinctive.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[831,1436,1481,1889]" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[831,1057,1481,1505]" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">Comparative notes</emphasis>
: Based on external characters (strongly transverse pronotum, coarsely punctate forebody), long marginal setae at the posterior margin of sternite VIII, and on the morphology of the aedeagus, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2021" box="[953,1092,1609,1633]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Leptusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="117" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auriculata">
<emphasis box="[953,1092,1609,1633]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">L. auriculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is assigned to the subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[832,993,1641,1665]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Leptusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="117" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Aphaireleptusa">
<emphasis box="[832,993,1641,1665]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">Aphaireleptusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It differs from other representatives of the subgenus recorded from mainland 
<collectingCountry box="[1293,1360,1673,1697]" name="China" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">China</collectingCountry>
by the combination of relatively pale colouration of the forebody and a bicoloured abdomen, a coarsely punctate forebody, and by the male sexual characters. For illustrations of other 
<taxonomicName box="[1032,1193,1801,1825]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Leptusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="117" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Aphaireleptusa">
<emphasis box="[1032,1193,1801,1825]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">Aphaireleptusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species known from mainland 
<collectingCountry box="[943,1010,1833,1857]" name="China" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">China</collectingCountry>
see 
<bibRefCitation author="PACE, R." box="[1058,1184,1833,1857]" pageId="14" pageNumber="117" pagination="751 - 760" refId="ref18439" refString="PACE, R. 1997: Specie del genere Leptusa in Cina. Monografia del genere Leptusa Kraatz: Supplemento VII (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). - Revue Suisse de Zoologie 104 (4): 751 - 760." type="journal article" year="1997">PACE (1997</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="PACE, R." box="[1195,1250,1833,1857]" pageId="14" pageNumber="117" pagination="369 - 376" refId="ref18480" refString="PACE, R. 1999: Nuove Leptusa della Cina. Monografia del genere Leptusa KRAATZ: Supplemento X (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). - Beitrage zur Entomologie, Berlin 49 (2): 369 - 376." type="journal article" year="1999">1999</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="PACE, R." box="[1261,1316,1833,1857]" pageId="14" pageNumber="117" pagination="151 - 160" refId="ref18520" refString="PACE, R. 2001: Nuove specie cinesi del genere Leptusa. Monografia del genere Leptusa KRAATZ: Supplemento XII (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). - Bollettino del Museo Regionale di Scienze Naturali, Torino 18: 151 - 160." type="journal article" year="2001">2001</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="PACE, R." box="[1327,1382,1833,1857]" pageId="14" pageNumber="117" pagination="295 - 299" refId="ref18654" refString="PACE, R. 2010: Biodiversita delle Leptusa della Cina, monografia del genere Leptusa KRAATZ. Supplemento XVI (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae, Aleocharinae). - Beitrage zur Entomologie, Keltern 60 (2): 295 - 299." type="journal article" year="2010">2010</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<bibRefCitation author="ASSING, V." box="[832,983,1865,1889]" pageId="14" pageNumber="117" pagination="971 - 1019" refId="ref17890" refString="ASSING, V. 2002: New species and records of Leptusa KRAATZ from the Palaearctic region (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae, Aleocharinae). - Linzer Biologische Beitrage 34 (2): 971 - 1019." type="journal article" year="2002">ASSING (2002</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="ASSING, V." box="[994,1052,1865,1889]" pageId="14" pageNumber="117" pagination="1157 - 1174" refId="ref17969" refString="ASSING, V. 2006: Six new species and additional records of Leptusa from northern Yunnan, China (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae, Aleocharinae). - Linzer Biologische Beitrage 38 (2): 1157 - 1174." type="journal article" year="2006">2006</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="118" pageId="14" pageNumber="117" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="14.[832,1437,1929,2049]" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[832,1197,1929,1953]" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">Distribution and natural history</emphasis>
: The specimens were found by sifting litter in several close localities in Cang (Diancang) Shan, Northwest 
<collectingRegion box="[1156,1242,1994,2017]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="14" pageNumber="117">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
, at high altitudes (
<quantity box="[838,988,2025,2049]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8649999999999998" metricValueMax="3.9899999999999998" metricValueMin="3.7399999999999998" pageId="14" pageNumber="117" unit="m" value="3865.0" valueMax="3990.0" valueMin="3740.0">3740–3990 m</quantity>
). The specimens bearing labels indicating
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,756,233,321]" pageId="15" pageNumber="118">
Emei Shan as the locality of collection were most likely mislabeled; for additional comments see the section on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2021" box="[151,267,298,321]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Leptusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="emeiana">
<emphasis box="[151,267,298,321]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="118">L. emeiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
